11:41.968 --> 11:47.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
might be carried on a weapon to
South Korea,
or Japan or even to the United
States. So,

11:47.440 --> 11:52.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I this is an acceleration and
escalation by
North Korea. And I think that
the United States

11:52.912 --> 11:55.381 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the world community need to
act with resolve.

11:55.415 --> 12:01.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Siegfried Hecker,
tell us, what
exactly is possible for North
Korea to have

12:01.287 --> 12:03.022 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
pulled off in this case?

12:03.056 --> 12:04.223 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SIEGFRIED HECKER, Former
Director, Los Alamos
National Laboratory: Well, it's
not clear

12:04.257 --> 12:06.259 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
exactly what they did.

12:06.292 --> 12:11.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As Ms. Sherman pointed out, they
did another
nuclear test. And, actually, my
greatest concern

12:11.664 --> 12:17.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is that they did the fourth
nuclear test.
With that nuclear test, they
clearly achieved

12:17.737 --> 12:23.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
greater sophistication, in most
likelihood
meaning being able to make the
bomb smaller,

12:23.109 --> 12:27.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lighter, and, therefore, have
greater reach,
if they're able to get them on a
missile.

12:27.413 --> 12:33.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whether it was a hydrogen test
or not, we
don't know. My sense is, we will
probably

12:33.653 --> 12:41.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
never really know. So far, from
what is the
information that's there, it
appears the size

12:41.628 --> 12:47.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the blast, in other words,
the power from
the seismic signal that can be
measured, it's

12:47.133 --> 12:54.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about the same level as the
third nuclear
test in 2013, which we put at
the level of

12:54.674 --> 13:01.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
approximately a Hiroshima bomb.
That's saying
10 to 15 kilotons.

13:01.147 --> 13:08.054 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Now, whether it actually
achieved the sophistication
of going to a fusion bomb --
that is, the

13:08.087 --> 13:14.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
normal bombs are fission or
atomic bombs -- the
fusion or hydrogen bomb, that is
a very big

13:14.394 --> 13:22.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
step technologically. And it's
not clear that
that was done, but we also can't
rule out

13:22.101 --> 13:24.671 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the North Koreans have made
a significant
advancement.

13:24.704 --> 13:28.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Wendy Sherman, we
talked about
the U.S. reaction. Let's walk
through some

13:28.741 --> 13:31.577 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the other intersectional
reaction, especially
China.

13:31.611 --> 13:36.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the past, they have been as
protective
of North Korea as any nation.
Not so today.

13:36.416 --> 13:38.117 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WENDY SHERMAN: Right.

13:38.151 --> 13:41.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, today, they said they are
resolutely
opposed to what North Korea has
done. Now

13:41.387 --> 13:47.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
