pointed out, is
calling for resolute action,
universal condemnation.

14:35.842 --> 14:38.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What difference does that make
for a rogue
state like North Korea?

14:38.978 --> 14:44.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIEGFRIED HECKER: Quite frankly,
I think none,
because we have been through
this at least

14:44.350 --> 14:51.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
since 2003 or so, when North
Korea pulled
out of a nonproliferation
treaty.

14:51.457 --> 14:56.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the attempts, not only by
the United States,
but by the international
community, has been,

14:56.763 --> 15:06.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in essence, to threaten North
Korea, to sanction
North Korea, to isolate North
Korea. And it

15:06.272 --> 15:12.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
simply hasn't worked. I think we
failed to
engage North Korea appropriately
when we had

15:12.779 --> 15:18.184 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
opportunities in these last 12
or 13 years.

15:18.217 --> 15:24.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whatever engagement was there
didn't work.
The bottom line is, over this
time, from 2003,

15:24.924 --> 15:32.298 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when they most likely built
their first primitive
device which they tested in
2006, until today,

15:32.331 --> 15:37.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they have gone from building a
device, 2003,
testing one that didn't work so
well in 2006,

15:37.703 --> 15:43.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to just now where they had the
fourth test,
the successful test.

15:43.342 --> 15:49.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in the meantime, at the
same time, they
have scaled up their ability to
make more

15:49.782 --> 15:54.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bombs. And so where we used to
have a problem
of having this country that
could perhaps

15:54.387 --> 15:59.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
build a simple nuclear device,
today, they
appear to have a nuclear
arsenal. That's of

15:59.926 --> 16:01.761 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
great concern.

16:01.794 --> 16:04.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, to me, that means we have
to do something
different than what's been done
over the last

16:04.797 --> 16:06.599 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
12 years.

16:06.632 --> 16:10.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Wendy Sherman, we
know that Kim
Jong-un is a tough read. Not
many people have

16:10.436 --> 16:15.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
