32:11.663 --> 32:13.431 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it's an employee benefit.

32:13.465 --> 32:18.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW SCHMERTZ: After months of
hard work,
the campaign gathered over
20,000 signatures

32:18.470 --> 32:23.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for Hildebrand to deliver to the
secretary
of state. But the opposing
lender-supported

32:23.208 --> 32:26.812 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
campaign also managed to gather
enough signatures
to get on the ballot.

32:26.845 --> 32:30.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE HILDEBRAND: The payday
lenders are going
to spend millions of dollars on
television

32:31.016 --> 32:35.720 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
trying to confuse voters and
misrepresent
our side.

32:35.754 --> 32:39.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW SCHMERTZ: So, the fight's
not over.
Hildebrand has one year to
convince South

32:39.925 --> 32:46.731 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Dakotans to vote for his
interest rate cap.
In the meantime, T.J. ended up
losing his

32:46.765 --> 32:50.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fight to save his leg. It was
amputated six
months after he lost his job.

32:50.602 --> 32:53.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KRISTI MCLAUGHLIN: It needs to
go at least
to there.

32:53.872 --> 32:58.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW SCHMERTZ: T.J. and Kristi
are now focused
on rehab, instead of the title
loan.

32:58.810 --> 33:03.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KRISTI MCLAUGHLIN: I told them
to come and
get the car. Take it. You know,
our world

33:03.815 --> 33:07.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has fallen out from underneath
us, and if
you want it that badly, come and
get it.

33:07.385 --> 33:10.789 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ANDREW SCHMERTZ: Over
Thanksgiving, the lender
repossessed their car.

33:10.822 --> 33:19.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
T.J. MCLAUGHLIN: People get
sick. And, you
know, if it's serious enough,
they can lose

33:19.231 --> 33:21.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
everything. We lost everything
in a matter
of a week, it seems like.

33:21.600 --> 33:24.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW SCHMERTZ: T.J. and Kristi
may have
to find their way out of this
devastation

33:24.202 --> 33:28.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on their own. But they hope, by
speaking out,
they can at least save other
South Dakotans

33:28.607 --> 33:32.444 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from becoming trapped in a
nightmare of high
interest rates.

33:32.477 --> 33:37.148 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," Andrew
Schmertz in
Sioux Falls, South Dakota.

33:37.182 --> 33:42.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now Hari Sreenivasan takes a
broader look
at the problems lower-income
Americans face

33:42.187 --> 33:44.522 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
when it comes to getting the
money they need.

33:44.556 --> 33:49.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: South Dakota
isn't the only
place where payday loans are
such a big problem.

33:49.928 --> 33:54.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While a few states have banned
or imposed
strict regulations on these
fringe lenders,

33:54.733 --> 34:00.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they're ubiquitous in most of
the country.
In fact, there are more payday
lending storefronts

34:00.138 --> 34:03.775 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
than there are Starbucks and
McDonald's combined.

34:03.808 --> 34:09.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In her book "How the Other Half
Banks," Mehrsa
Baradaran explores the booming
industry providing

34:09.414 --> 34:16.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
financial services to the poor
at exorbitant
costs and offers some more
equitable solutions.

34:16.054 --> 34:17.756 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thanks for joining us.

34:17.789 --> 34:22.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, why -- where is this gap
created? And
why isn't there an incentive for
all banks

34:22.360 --> 34:24.129 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to reach out to all people with
money?

34:24.162 --> 34:26.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MEHRSA BARADARAN, Author, "How
the Other Half
Banks": The gap is fairly new.

34:26.097 --> 34:31.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, starting in the 1980s, a lot
of community
banks started shutting down
branches in lower-income

34:31.336 --> 34:35.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
areas, inner-city neighborhoods,
areas where
their profit margins were lower
than in other

34:35.740 --> 34:41.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
areas. And so part of it is,
it's higher cost
to lend to someone or to take a
small deposit

34:41.947 --> 34:47.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
than it is to get a big deposit.
Right? Your
overhead is the same whether
you're, you know,

34:47.085 --> 34:54.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
taking in $100,000 vs. taking in
$500, but
your revenue off of that
$100,000 is much

34:54.693 --> 34:57.195 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
higher than it is off of that
small deposit.

34:57.228 --> 35:02.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so these banks started
leaving these areas.
And part of it is that the
government deregulatory

35:02.600 --> 35:07.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
forces allowed them to merge and
form these
huge conglomerates such as Bank
of America.

35:07.272 --> 35:12.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, as these banks leave, they
leave this
void for banking service. And
this is a void

35:12.043 --> 35:16.648 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that quickly is filled by these
fringe lenders,
so payday loans, check cashing.

35:16.681 --> 35:19.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, when you
go through
certain cities, just like there
are food deserts

35:20.018 --> 35:23.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where you don't have a grocery
store, it seems
like there are almost bank
deserts, where

35:23.221 --> 35:26.458 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it's populated primarily with
these lenders
that you're talking about.

35:26.491 --> 35:28.259 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How much money is there to be
made?

35:28.293 --> 35:34.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MEHRSA BARADARAN: It's an $89
billion industry
yearly. And it doesn't seem that
way.

35:34.265 --> 35:37.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when you go into these
neighborhoods,
these check cashers or payday
lenders, they

35:37.702 --> 35:44.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
seem like neighborhood joints.
But they're
really sort of multinational
corporations.

35:44.309 --> 35:47.112 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're large, very profitable
organizations.

35:47.145 --> 35:52.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they have this, what I call
a facade of
informality, right? So it seems
as though,

35:52.083 --> 35:55.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
look, they speak your language.
They're in
your neighborhood, but, really,
behind them,

35:55.620 --> 35:59.824 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
there is a lot of bank
financing. These are
very sort of corporate, big, big
firms.

35:59.858 --> 36:04.262 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: These
companies are going
to say, look, I'm taking a
greater risk. This

36:04.295 --> 36:08.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is a person that is not as
creditworthy as
someone who maybe walks into a
Bank of America

36:08.633 --> 36:13.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with a much larger amount of
assets, right,
so shouldn't I be able to charge
a higher

36:13.805 --> 36:15.774 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
interest rate to get them this
money fast?

36:15.807 --> 36:20.178 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MEHRSA BARADARAN: It is
certainly a higher
risk to lend to someone who's
low-income.

36:20.211 --> 36:24.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, there's a lot of
studies to show
that the price that they're
actually charging

36:24.416 --> 36:29.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
isn't the cost of the loan. It's
also fairly
misleading when you compare it
to the credit

36:29.287 --> 36:32.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
markets that the middle class
and higher income
have access to.

36:32.924 --> 36:38.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the big points of the
book is,
even assuming that this is a
market price

36:38.663 --> 36:43.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they're charging and it is
the cost of
credit because of the risks and
the defaults,

36:43.535 --> 36:48.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
et cetera, the rest of us don't
pay market
prices for credit.

36:48.306 --> 36:52.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The credit markets, whether it's
for our mortgages,
our student loans, any sort of
bank credit

36:52.844 --> 36:55.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you get is heavily subsidized by
the federal
government.

36:55.547 --> 36:57.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The book is
called "How
the Other Half Banks."

36:57.582 --> 37:01.019 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mehrsa Baradaran, thanks so much
for joining
us.

37:01.052 --> 37:08.159 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MEHRSA BARADARAN: Thank you.

37:08.193 --> 37:16.668 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The U.S.
Department of Homeland
Security conducted a series of
raids over

37:16.701 --> 37:22.707 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
New Year's weekend on
undocumented immigrants
in a number of states, including
Georgia,

37:22.740 --> 37:25.043 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
North Carolina and Texas.

37:25.076 --> 37:30.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Federal officials said they have
taken more
than 100 people into custody,
most of whom

37:30.115 --> 37:35.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
arrived in the U.S. within the
past two years,
and are now awaiting
deportation.

37:35.887 --> 37:40.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But immigration groups are
fighting back,
and the nation's highest
immigration court

37:40.658 --> 37:44.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
issued a ruling last night to
delay some of
the deportations.

37:44.662 --> 37:51.503 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Even before these moves,
hundreds of thousands
of undocumented immigrants were
being deported

37:51.536 --> 37:55.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
annually. And for those who grew
up in the
U.S., that means they have found
themselves

37:55.840 --> 37:59.110 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
living in what feels like a
foreign country.

37:59.144 --> 38:03.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Special correspondent Fred de
Sam Lazaro reports
from Mexico.

38:03.915 --> 38:09.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Miguel
Ramirez works in
Mexico City, and an almost daily
ritual is

38:09.487 --> 38:15.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to call his mother in Saint
Louis. He lived
there too, until he was deported
three years

38:15.160 --> 38:18.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ago, and banned for life from
ever reentering
the U.S.

38:18.930 --> 38:21.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MIGUEL RAMIREZ, Returnee: She's
-- she's devastated,
you know?

38:21.933 --> 38:28.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: The shy
23-year-old, brought
to the U.S. by his mother as a
young child,

38:28.339 --> 38:32.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
admits he fell in with the wrong
crowd. He
got caught in a burglary and his
sentence

38:32.944 --> 38:35.079 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
was community service, until:

38:35.113 --> 38:42.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIGUEL RAMIREZ: I get a note
from the judge
telling me that, because you're
an illegal

38:42.754 --> 38:47.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
immigrant, you don't qualify for
this program,
and you're going to have to
start doing your

38:47.125 --> 38:48.993 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
time.

38:49.027 --> 38:51.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Most of his
time was actually
done in immigrant detention
centers before

38:51.262 --> 38:53.431 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he was dropped off at the
Mexican border.

38:53.464 --> 38:56.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIGUEL RAMIREZ: That, to me, was
rough. It
was one of the roughest things
ever. But,

38:56.601 --> 38:59.437 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, I had to accept it. I
had no choice.

38:59.470 --> 39:03.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Ramirez is
one of several
young Mexican returnees profiled
in a book

39:03.875 --> 39:09.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
called "Los Otros Dreamers" by
scholar and
social activist Jill Anderson.

39:09.247 --> 39:13.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some have committed felonies,
she says, but
the vast majority have no
criminal history

39:13.952 --> 39:15.787 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
or just minor infractions.

39:15.820 --> 39:19.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JILL ANDERSON, Author, "Los
Otros Dreamers":
For many, it's contact with
their local police

39:19.190 --> 39:27.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for anything from underage
drinking, accusations
from a neighbor or friends. One
young woman

39:27.365 --> 39:30.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was baby-sitting and had a
problem with the
family.

39:30.335 --> 39:35.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: In 2012,
President Obama
issued an executive order that
allowed the

39:35.607 --> 39:39.777 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
children of undocumented
workers, many of
whom had grown up in the United
States, the

39:39.811 --> 39:41.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
option to remain.

39:41.679 --> 39:44.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States:
Specifically for certain young
people sometimes

39:44.816 --> 39:46.718 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
called dreamers.

39:46.751 --> 39:50.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: The order
came after Congress
rejected similar legislation
called the DREAM

39:50.622 --> 39:56.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Act. And it came after perhaps a
half-million
young Mexicans were either
deported or chose

39:56.327 --> 39:57.629 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to return.

39:57.662 --> 40:00.932 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: This was a cute guy I had
a crush on
in my freshman year.

40:00.965 --> 40:05.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Viridiana
and Maggie belong
to Los Otros Dreamers, or the
Other Dreamers,

40:05.770 --> 40:09.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a group that mostly meets
online, brought
together by Anderson's book.

40:09.974 --> 40:15.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Viridiana says, growing up in
Iowa, she felt
no stigma over her illegal
status.

40:15.613 --> 40:19.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIRIDIANA, Returnee: My parents
always told
me, never tell anyone that we're
here undocumented.

40:19.250 --> 40:24.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, at first, it was just
kind of like,
OK, I'm young and who cares?
Like, I mean,

40:24.522 --> 40:27.225 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what's so -- what's wrong in
being undocumented?

40:27.258 --> 40:33.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: It was no
big deal growing
up, she says, until:

40:33.164 --> 40:35.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Dad goes to work one day and...

40:35.300 --> 40:40.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIRIDIANA: Never comes home.
They went to
his workplace, and they took
him.

40:40.638 --> 40:45.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Twenty-two
years after
he arrived and settled quietly
in small-town

40:45.877 --> 40:52.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iowa, Juan Vargas (ph) was
arrested and deported.
That brought abrupt, wrenching
decisions for

40:52.417 --> 40:54.252 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
others in the family.

40:54.285 --> 41:01.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIRIDIANA: My older sister, she
-- she decided
to stay in the United States,
and I totally

41:01.225 --> 41:07.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
understand that. It is my home
too. I do miss
it, but, you know, I would
rather stay with

41:07.765 --> 41:09.500 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
my parents.

41:09.534 --> 41:14.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Viridiana
quit her job
and, with her mother, returned
to Mexico,

41:14.105 --> 41:15.873 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
against her father's wishes.

41:15.907 --> 41:20.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIRIDIANA: He said: "I don't
want you here.
I don't want you to be here.
Just stay home."

41:20.178 --> 41:24.582 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO:
Twenty-five-year-old Maggie
got the same advice from her
parents. Home

41:24.615 --> 41:29.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for her was Dalton, Georgia,
where she too
felt no different from her wide
circle of

41:29.821 --> 41:31.489 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
friends until high school.

41:31.522 --> 41:35.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAGGIE, Returnee: I wanted to go
to work.
I wanted to find scholarships.
That's when

41:35.526 --> 41:41.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
things started to -- wait, so
you're different?
That's when I started to
actually recognize

41:41.933 --> 41:46.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was undocumented and that I
wasn't -- I
didn't have the same
opportunities.

41:46.070 --> 41:50.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Lacking
money to go to
college or get a legal,
good-paying job, she

41:50.608 --> 41:56.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
decided, agonizingly, to move to
Mexico, a
country she'd left at age 3.

41:56.280 --> 42:04.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAGGIE: My parents stayed. I
came by myself
at 18. And it was during -- this
month, it

42:04.322 --> 42:10.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was like if somebody had died
inside of me,
because it was like, OK, bye,
house, bye,

42:10.828 --> 42:15.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
church, bye, friends, bye,
school, bye, dog.
I mean, I wasn't prepared.

42:15.566 --> 42:21.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Mexico
wasn't prepared
for her or other returnees
either. Until recently,

42:21.572 --> 42:28.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. education credentials were
not even recognized.
Aside from official
indifference, Viridiana

42:28.179 --> 42:32.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
says there's social stigma and
suspicion that
they are criminal deportees.

42:32.750 --> 42:37.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIRIDIANA: Why are you back?
That's like the
first thing that they ask. Why
are you back?

42:37.221 --> 42:39.824 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What is the problem? They treat
us like crap.

42:39.857 --> 42:41.759 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Author Jill
Anderson:

42:41.793 --> 42:47.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JILL ANDERSON: They realize,
wow, I thought
I was Mexican. I don't talk like
a Mexican

42:47.298 --> 42:57.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because of my accent when I
speak Spanish.
People actually will call me
pocho or gringo,

42:57.074 --> 42:59.410 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and question as to why I'm even
here.

42:59.444 --> 43:05.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: There is one
industry
that is happy they're here: call
centers,

43:05.082 --> 43:07.518 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
whose operators speak American
English.

43:07.552 --> 43:12.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: I get to meet people from
all over
the United States when they call
my employer

43:12.089 --> 43:14.025 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with their customer service
questions.

43:14.058 --> 43:18.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Call centers
have proliferated
across Mexican cities, their
promotional videos

43:19.030 --> 43:25.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like this one on the Internet
geared to American
customers. It's one of few
places where returnees

43:25.603 --> 43:31.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can find work. They even waived
the requirement
of a high school diploma for
Miguel Ramirez,

43:31.642 --> 43:33.544 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and he says they pay a decent
wage.

43:33.578 --> 43:37.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIGUEL RAMIREZ: This job is very
tedious.
You feel like you're getting
nowhere. It doesn't

43:37.548 --> 43:41.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
make me feel very successful or
proud of myself,
to be honest with you. I want to
do something

43:41.719 --> 43:43.488 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
more.

43:43.521 --> 43:46.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Call centers
do report
a high turnover. And living in
Mexico, where

43:46.491 --> 43:51.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
many people struggle with life's
more basic
needs, Viridiana says it was
hard for her

43:51.729 --> 43:54.599 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to deal with what she saw as
trivial concerns.

43:54.632 --> 43:58.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIRIDIANA: I couldn't handle the
calls. I
was just like, oh, my God, like,
these people

43:58.336 --> 44:04.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that -- why are they just
complaining about
their dish service? Like,
really? And then

44:04.675 --> 44:09.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm thinking like, girl, you
used to be one
of those dish people that would
call and be

44:09.313 --> 44:11.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
like, what is wrong with you?
Your service
sucks.

44:11.582 --> 44:12.950 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

44:12.984 --> 44:15.720 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VIRIDIANA: Like, that really
bothers me, and
I cannot do this job.

44:15.753 --> 44:21.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: She now
works as a transportation
dispatcher and lives with her
parents. Her

44:21.626 --> 44:27.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mother, Patrice Hidalgo, says,
on a fraction
of their former income, life
here is difficult.

44:27.665 --> 44:32.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PATRICE HIDALGO, Returnee
(through translator):
Here, because of my age I can't
get a job.

44:32.537 --> 44:38.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the security situation is
not good. It's
much worse now in Mexico than it
was before

44:38.175 --> 44:40.044 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
we left.

44:40.077 --> 44:44.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And the
security situation
along the migration routes to
the U.S., now

44:44.549 --> 44:51.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
overrun by gangs trafficking in
drugs and
people, keeps many from fleeing
Mexico again.

44:51.122 --> 44:53.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you ever contemplate going
back to the
United States illegally?

44:53.858 --> 45:00.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIGUEL RAMIREZ: I do. I do
contemplate it,
not a lot, because there's a
risk.

45:00.431 --> 45:05.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: For her
part, Maggie got
a job teaching English, and she
attends college,

45:05.836 --> 45:08.005 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hoping to get into tourism
promotion.

45:08.039 --> 45:15.846 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAGGIE: I want to travel more in
this country.
I know it's beautiful. I know it
has many

45:15.880 --> 45:19.917 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
positive things. And I'm
starting to see that
beautiful side of Mexico.

45:19.951 --> 45:25.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And she
plans to visit
the U.S. again, and often, only
now with passport

45:26.023 --> 45:27.592 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and visa.

45:27.625 --> 45:32.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," this is
Fred de Sam
Lazaro in Leon, Mexico.

45:32.096 --> 45:37.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Fred's reporting
is a partnership
with the Under-Told Stories
Project at the

45:37.468 --> 45:43.641 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
University of St. Thomas in
