45:43.674 --> 45:56.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Now to an inspiring
story about
one of last year's MacArthur
grant winners

45:56.821 --> 45:59.557 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and how design can change lives.

45:59.590 --> 46:05.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Jackie
Judd reports
for our Breakthroughs series on
innovation

46:05.229 --> 46:07.064 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and invention.

46:07.098 --> 46:14.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: In the hands of
Alex Truesdell,
a simple piece of cardboard
turns into a world

46:14.405 --> 46:19.577 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of possibilities. Her life's
mission began
by accident.

46:19.610 --> 46:24.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Truesdell was rooting around in
a closet at
a school where she was teaching
and found

46:24.215 --> 46:27.051 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a chair that had been made for a
disabled
adult.

46:27.084 --> 46:30.788 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ALEX TRUESDELL, Founder,
Adaptive Design Association:
The armrest and the footrest on
it were actually

46:30.821 --> 46:34.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at different heights on the left
side than
the right side. And I asked
about it, and

46:34.959 --> 46:38.863 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they said, oh, that's made of
cardboard. And
I think my head exploded.

46:38.896 --> 46:40.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Why did your head
explode?

46:40.765 --> 46:44.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEX TRUESDELL: The idea that
you could take
that material and turn it into
what you needed,

46:44.402 --> 46:46.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that, if you needed something,
you could make
something.

46:46.937 --> 46:53.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Truesdell has been
making something
ever since with her triple-ply
cardboard,

46:53.310 --> 46:59.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
glue and simple tools. In New
York City, at
the Adaptive Design Association,
which she

46:59.650 --> 47:05.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
founded, cardboard furniture and
learning
tools are built for children
with disabilities.

47:05.556 --> 47:10.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEX TRUESDELL: It makes the
child, one, believe
in their own capacity, and then
everyone who

47:11.028 --> 47:16.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
knows and loves the child
believe in what
they're able to do. I think it
upends the

47:16.467 --> 47:22.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prognosis, because, so often,
unfortunately,
the word disability signals
broken, can't,

47:22.506 --> 47:24.208 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
isn't.

47:24.241 --> 47:31.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Creating this very
individualized
furniture often involves a house
call. In

47:31.716 --> 47:38.723 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
suburban New Jersey,
21-month-old Austin Kellenberger
is getting his first fitting for
a chair and

47:38.756 --> 47:40.524 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a table.

47:40.558 --> 47:42.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KELLENBERGER, Father of
Austin: Austin
has significant motor
development issues.

47:42.860 --> 47:45.563 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He has difficulty even moving
his arm.

47:45.596 --> 47:51.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Today, even as a
toddler, dad
John Kellenberger says, Austin
feels apart

47:51.635 --> 47:54.138 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from his twin brother and older
sister.

47:54.171 --> 47:57.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KELLENBERGER: Oftentimes,
my other son,
Dylan (ph), and my daughter,
Savannah (ph),

47:57.441 --> 48:03.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will be playing at the table
with toys. He's
not able to do that. So, you do
see he is

48:03.280 --> 48:06.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very frustrated. He wants to --
he's a very
social boy. He wants to be part
of the group.

48:06.884 --> 48:11.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: This furniture is
supposed to
make that possible, to make
Austin feel less

48:11.989 --> 48:14.859 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
different and to build his
physical strength.

48:14.892 --> 48:21.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEX TRUESDELL: Right now, he
fatigues quickly,
but he hasn't had the right
chair in order

48:21.632 --> 48:29.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to build strength. So, the
angles of this
will actually give him a bit of
a challenge.

48:29.640 --> 48:36.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Cardboard is
relatively inexpensive,
readily available and really
sturdy, a trifecta

48:36.380 --> 48:43.120 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
for growing kids and for
families, often burdened
by medical costs, who are asked
for contributions

48:43.154 --> 48:47.925 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of just $500.

48:47.958 --> 48:53.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Austin's chair is measured, and
measured again,
and cut to within an eighth of
an inch, so

48:53.664 --> 48:56.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it is just exactly right for the
little boy.

48:56.167 --> 49:01.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEX TRUESDELL: We need a custom
fit in an
off-the-rack world. And if it
doesn't fit,

49:01.071 --> 49:05.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if the child struggles, and
they're already
struggling, it's going to use up
that energy

49:05.976 --> 49:11.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and be discouraging. And then
they or someone
else will give up, and get the
wrong idea

49:11.715 --> 49:18.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about the child's potential, as
opposed to
being inspired enough to change
the thing,

49:18.489 --> 49:20.224 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
change the environment to make
it work.

49:20.257 --> 49:24.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Truesdell saw that
happen in
her own family, and it was a
life-changer.

49:25.029 --> 49:30.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her uncle turned conventional
household tools
into something her aunt, who had
lost the

49:30.201 --> 49:32.102 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
use of her hands, could
manipulate.

49:32.136 --> 49:38.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEX TRUESDELL: My uncle was
able to repurpose
things, bend things that were
too straight,

49:38.075 --> 49:43.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cut things that were too long,
connect things.
And that thought, that you could
engineer

49:43.080 --> 49:47.718 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
change to suit her specific
needs, is really
the root of this.

49:47.751 --> 49:52.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: The workshop has
turned out pieces
this year for more than 200 New
York area

49:52.990 --> 49:56.227 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
kids, but many more children can
use them.

49:56.260 --> 50:02.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Alex Truesdell and her team
spend as much
time teaching as they do
designing and building.

50:02.299 --> 50:06.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the last several years alone,
they have
led several hundred design
workshops and have

50:06.570 --> 50:11.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
answered inquiries from around
the globe.
As a result, these cardboard
creations are

50:11.175 --> 50:17.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
being built in about six U.S.
locations and
in countries as diverse as
India, Romania

50:17.314 --> 50:19.049 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and Peru.

50:19.083 --> 50:22.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEX TRUESDELL: We try to use
methods here
that could be used anywhere in
the world.

50:22.152 --> 50:28.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, any technique, anything we
make, the materials
we use, we want other people to
see what we

50:28.525 --> 50:33.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
do and copy it. We really are
trying to supply
the movement, so that we would
inspire imitation,

50:33.764 --> 50:36.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
cooperation, and collaboration
throughout.

50:36.200 --> 50:43.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Truesdell sees some
children
only once and others throughout
their lives.

50:43.340 --> 50:48.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She met New York City teenager
Hannah Auchincloss
(ph) as a toddler, when Hannah's
mother, Tracy

50:48.646 --> 50:53.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ehrlich, was struggling to find
a chair in
which Hannah could feed sitting
up.

50:53.617 --> 50:56.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TRACY EHRLICH, Mother of Hannah:
She couldn't
do any of those things, and she
was much too

50:56.887 --> 50:58.689 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
small for conventional
wheelchairs.

50:58.722 --> 51:02.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: So there was
nothing you could
have ordered online, or gone
into a medical

51:02.860 --> 51:06.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
supply store and say, that's
what I need,
that's what would help her?

51:06.830 --> 51:09.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TRACY EHRLICH: No, absolutely
not, because
she was so young.

51:09.133 --> 51:14.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Ehrlich has lost
track of all
the pieces Truesdell has made
for Hannah,

51:14.138 --> 51:19.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and even some for her sisters,
so the family
feels bound together, instead of
separated

51:19.576 --> 51:26.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by Hannah's challenges. But some
pieces stand
out, like the bike, the scooter
and a beloved

51:26.317 --> 51:29.553 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rocking chair that Hannah can
get moving on
her own.

51:29.586 --> 51:36.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEX TRUESDELL: The experience
of moving herself
at just -- one thing she can
really control

51:36.694 --> 51:38.629 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
every day.

51:38.662 --> 51:42.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TRACY EHRLICH: I think that all
of the different
pieces of equipment have opened
up the possibilities

51:42.833 --> 51:48.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for her, the opportunities for
her to interact
with her world, interact with
the people who

51:48.472 --> 51:50.374 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
are around her.

51:50.407 --> 51:54.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: In New Jersey,
Austin Kellenberger
is just beginning to interact
with his world.

51:54.945 --> 52:00.751 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
His furniture has been
delivered. And what
most see as a simple chair, his
parents, John

52:00.784 --> 52:02.786 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and Danielle (ph), see as
transformative.

52:02.820 --> 52:07.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KELLENBERGER: I want Austin
to reach
whatever the potential that he
has. I want

52:07.624 --> 52:11.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
him to reach that. I don't know
what that
is. The doctors don't know what
that is at

52:11.462 --> 52:16.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this point. But whatever it is,
I want to
give him every chance to meet
that. And this

52:16.633 --> 52:20.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is one of the -- frankly, this
is one of the
things that's helping us do
that.

52:20.104 --> 52:25.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Alex Truesdell
started out as
a teacher for the blind. What
she has done

52:25.042 --> 52:31.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is let children, thousands of
them, see and
experience movement, growth and
confidence,

52:32.016 --> 52:36.553 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all through a simple piece of
cardboard and
a lot of ingenuity.

52:36.587 --> 52:42.760 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is Jackie Judd in New York
for the "NewsHour."

52:42.793 --> 52:54.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And now for our
"NewsHour"
Shares, something that caught
our eye that

52:54.405 --> 52:56.907 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we thought might be of interest
to you too.

52:56.940 --> 53:02.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. Geological Survey on
Tuesday released
its first ever digital map of
the nation's

53:02.646 --> 53:09.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
northernmost state. In vibrant
colors, it
reveals thousands of Alaska's
geological details

53:09.353 --> 53:15.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that can be used to contribute
to mineral,
energy, hazard, and other types
of scientific

53:15.392 --> 53:17.161 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
assessments.

53:17.194 --> 53:21.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Shades of red represent areas
where rare-earth
elements, like those used in
electronics,

53:21.899 --> 53:27.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are most likely to be uncovered,
while green
represents the rocks where most
dinosaur fossils

53:27.905 --> 53:35.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are found. It took Frederic
Wilson, along
with a team of a dozen unpaid
retired scientists,

53:35.412 --> 53:43.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some 20 years to create. They
drew on more
than 750 references, some dating
back to the

53:43.253 --> 53:45.022 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
early 1900s.

53:45.055 --> 53:49.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Scientists say a map like this
could help
identify new earthquake fault
zones and help

53:49.860 --> 53:53.931 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the oil and gas industry scope
out their next
big find.

53:53.964 --> 53:55.799 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: That's cool.

